hf_hf1.text: Miss Hunter cut her hair at the request of Mr. Rucastle.

hf_hf2.text: Mr. Rucastle complimented Miss Hunter on her appearance after cutting her hair.

hf_hf3.text: Miss Hunter wore an electric-blue dress provided by Mr. Rucastle.

hf_hf4.text: Mr. Rucastle told funny stories to Miss Hunter in the drawing-room.

hf_hf5.text: Mrs. Rucastle did not smile during Mr. Rucastle's storytelling.

hf_hf6.text: Miss Hunter observed a man in a grey suit looking at her from the Southampton Road.

hf_hf7.text: Mrs. Rucastle identified the man in the road as impertinent.

hf_hf8.text: Mr. Rucastle warned Miss Hunter not to go near the mastiff at night.

hf_hf9.text: Miss Hunter saw a giant dog on the lawn at night.

hf_hf10.text: Miss Hunter found her own hair locked in a drawer at the Copper Beeches.

hf_hf11.text: Mr. Rucastle appeared angry when he came out of a locked door.

hf_hf12.text: Miss Hunter observed that one wing of the house was not inhabited.

hf_hf13.text: Miss Hunter saw Toller carrying a large black linen bag.

hf_hf14.text: Miss Hunter entered a locked room in the house.

hf_hf15.text: Miss Hunter heard footsteps and saw a shadow in the locked room.

hf_hf16.text: Mr. Rucastle threatened Miss Hunter after she entered the locked room.

hf_hf17.text: Miss Hunter planned to send a wire to Holmes for help.

hf_hf18.text: Holmes deduced that Miss Hunter was brought to impersonate someone.

hf_hf19.text: Mr. Rucastle imprisoned his daughter, Miss Alice Rucastle.

hf_hf20.text: Miss Hunter was similar in appearance to Miss Alice Rucastle.

hf_hf21.text: Mr. Fowler was in love with Miss Alice Rucastle.

hf_hf22.text: Mrs. Toller revealed information about Miss Alice Rucastle's imprisonment.

hf_hf23.text: Mr. Rucastle wanted Miss Alice Rucastle to sign a paper regarding her money.

hf_hf24.text: Miss Alice Rucastle suffered from brain-fever due to her father's pressure.

hf_hf25.text: Helen Stoner's stepfather, Dr. Roylott, has a passion for Indian animals, including a cheetah and a baboon.

hf_hf26.text: Holmes noted that the flooring and walls of the room where Julia died were sound and secure.

hf_hf27.text: Holmes planned to visit Stoke Moran to investigate the case further.

hf_hf28.text: Dr. Grimesby Roylott confronted Holmes and Watson, accusing them of meddling in his affairs.

hf_hf29.text: Holmes discovered that the deceased wife’s will indicated financial motives for Dr. Roylott to prevent his stepdaughters' marriages.

hf_hf30.text: Ryder planned to hide the blue stone in a goose to escape detection.

axes.name: Emotion vs. Logic
axes.description: This axis represents the tension between emotional responses and logical reasoning, highlighting characters' approaches to situations.

axes.name: Social Status
axes.description: This axis indicates the social hierarchy and status of characters, from common individuals to nobility and royalty.

axes.name: Mystery vs. Clarity
axes.description: This axis reflects the degree of mystery present in the narrative, contrasting ambiguous situations with clear resolutions.

axes.name: Action vs. Inaction
axes.description: This axis measures the level of activity or passivity exhibited by characters in response to challenges or dilemmas.

axes.name: Time Progression
axes.description: This axis tracks the temporal flow of events, from past recollections to present actions and future implications.
